               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340904-228-person1353">
                  ALEXANDER 
                  WHITE
               <interp inst="t18340904-228-person1353" type="surname" value="WHITE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-228-person1353" type="given" value="ALEXANDER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-228-person1353" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was in <placeName id="t18340904-228-crimeloc1280">Chiswell-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18340904-228-crimeloc1280" type="placeName" value="Chiswell-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18340904-228-crimeloc1280" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18340904-228-off1278 t18340904-228-crimeloc1280"></join> on the 27th of August, about half-past eight o'clock in the morning, and saw the prisoners in company together - I watched them, and saw them cross the street to Sowerby's, the pawnbrokers, and loiter about for some time - they then crossed over to Wood's shop - a saw laid in the passage - I saw stone go in, and when he came out he had the saw in his hand - Thompson was waiting outside for him - I directly went over to Mr. Wood, and saw Harrison, and told him - I pointed them out when they got to Bunhill-row - I had seen Stone hand the saw to Thompson - I called "Stop thief," we overtook them, and they were secured at the corner of Jewin-street.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340904-228-person1354">
                  ROBERT 
                  HARRISON
               <interp inst="t18340904-228-person1354" type="surname" value="HARRISON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-228-person1354" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-228-person1354" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am errand boy to Mr. Wood - White gave me information - I went in pursuit - I overtook the prisoners, and they were secured - here is the saw.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340904-228-person1355">
                  EDWARD 
                  McDONAL
               <interp inst="t18340904-228-person1355" type="surname" value="McDONAL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-228-person1355" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-228-person1355" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a City policeman - I have had the saw ever since I took the prisoners into custody.</p>
               <p>RICHARD MASON WOOD. I am a <rs id="t18340904-228-viclabel1281" type="occupation">printer</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18340904-228-victim1352 t18340904-228-viclabel1281"></join> - this is my saw - it lay near the doorway.</p>
               <p>Thompson's Defence. I was passing along the street, somebody going by, with a fustian coat on, dropped something - I picked it up - it was the saw - I did not run away with it till after I got some distance - when I heard a cry of"Stop him with the saw" - I then turned back, and gave the saw to the witness.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183409040120"></xptr>Ston's Defence. I know nothing of Thompson. I was looking about for a situation - I happened to ask him if he knew of one - he said he did not - I went on - he said,"Good bye" - and shortly after the witness cried "Stop thief" - I ran with the mob, and when they got down the street they gave me in charge.</p>
               <p>(Mr. Jones, solicitor, of Brunswick-square, gave Thompson a good character.)</p>
               <p>THOMPSON - <rs id="t18340904-228-verdict1282" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18340904-228-verdict1282" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 17.</p>
